2. PLANE CURVES
The developments in the last section include the theory of plane curves as a special case. We can also easily give an independent treatment of plane curves, since it has the advantage that the plane can be taken to be oriented; an orientation of a plane may be given bv a fixed oriented frame Ox 1x 2 at a point 0, called the origin, in the plane: which now consists of only two orthogonal unit vectors.
Most theorems in this section are global theorems on plane curves. which may be contrasted with local theorems. The latter theorems are concerned with the invariant properties in a neighborhood of a general point of a curve, whereas the former ones view a curve as a whole. For instance, the length of a closed curve and the area enclosed by a closed plane curve are simple global properties, since each requires the entire curve. Similarly, the simple theorem that the number of points of intersection of a straight line with a conic in the same plane is at most two is global.

